<section class="section section--alt" id="checklist-quickbooks-setup-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What this checklist is &mdash; and what it isn&rsquo;t.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A QuickBooks setup checklist is the short, ordered list of things you configure once when you first open a company file, so that every report, invoice, and reconciliation after that is built on solid ground. Get these right at the start and the file stays clean; skip one and you tend to discover it months later, mid-cleanup. The nine items below cover the whole arc: company identity and fiscal year, the plan or product you&rsquo;re on, the chart of accounts, opening balances as of your start date, connected bank and card accounts, your customers, vendors, and items, sales tax, users, and the key preferences that shape daily work.</p>
      <p>What this page <em>is</em>: the condensed, printable tick-list &mdash; the items to check off at a glance, in order, free to print or screenshot with no email wall. What it <em>isn&rsquo;t</em>: a step-by-step walkthrough. For that &mdash; where each setting lives, the exact clicks, and how QuickBooks Online and QuickBooks Desktop differ &mdash; use the fuller <a href="/quickbooks/setup/checklist/">QuickBooks setup guide</a>. Use this one to track progress; reach for the full guide when you want the detail behind a step.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

